name: Kallang Riverside Park
review_text:
Love the walk at kallang riverside! Already went for a few times! It‚Äôs a full 10.5km loop.

Start on the left path towards kallang mrt. Cross the kallang bridge and immediately u-turn towards the opposite river bank at the end of the kallang bridge.

Head towards stadium, then tanjong rhu bridge, the pebble bay condo, then towards Marina barrage.

Once you reach Marina barrage, it‚Äôs 5.8km and I took about 1.15hrs cos I am doing brisk walk.

Then go towards garden by the bay, then cross the helix bridge, cross the road and head towards singapore flyer, then follow the path back to kallang riverside.

Whole journey 2hrs.10.5km.

Here‚Äôs another the tip!

Must start the walk before 7am! Nothing later than that, else when you reach singapore flyer, the sun is very hot!

I tried once at 7.45am, regretted it.

name: Kallang Riverside Park
review_text:
This park is one that is less-trodden, with human traffic that shies greatly from that in MacRitchie or East Coast. It is neither prominent or large in scale, but it does offer some scenic views as one walks along the Kallang River, opposite the National Stadium.

Some interesting wildlife can be found here, such as banyan and sea grape trees. The occasional pavilion can be found along the park's trail where small groupies can celebrate their birthdays and the like. There is also a clearing somewhere along the trail where you can have a game of badminton, with markings drawn out on the ground. This clearing is exactly where one of Senoko gasworks's refineries was once situated. Furthermore, there are a few designated fishing spots to spend an idle (but extremely arid and hot) afternoon at. Just don't expect long challenging hikes, walks or runs here, and look for barbecue pits elsewhere.

If you'd like to get to know the park better, the Mahota Commune @ Kitchener complex offers free guided Sunday walks (try Googling for it) for anyone from the public as part of their CSR/Community Involvement/Brand Awareness initiatives. This was how I got to learn more about the park's history.
